Is Black Friday still chaos?? Though the significance of Black Friday is more of a state of mind now that its namesake promotions stretch across the holiday week and even earlier, online sales are already exceeding expectations: Consumers spent $6.1 billion on Thanksgiving Day alone, up 8.8 percent from last year, according to Adobe Analytics.  They are projected to spend $10.8 billion on Black Friday. Meanwhile, foot traffic veered from steady to brisk for many retailers. The scene at one upscale mall in Dallas was reminiscent of Black Fridays past, complete with long lines to get into stores like LEGO, Glossier and Sephora. The turnout reaffirms that it‚Äôs a big day for deal-hungry consumers even as the ‚Äúbarbell effect‚Äù widens the divide between what higher- and lower-earning Americans can spend, said Adam Davis, managing director of the retail division at Wells Fargo Capital Finance. There were still spaces to be found at a Walmart parking lot here at midmorning. Inside, shoppers skimmed the electronics aisles, with a few walking away with a flat screen TV or sound bars in their baskets. Others leisurely sifted through bins of holiday socks and fleece pants.

While the president had pledged several times not to pardon or commute Hunter Biden‚Äôs sentences for federal crimes, many close to him had expected the pardon would come, given the president‚Äôs loyalty to his family. Biden faces few political ramifications for the move, since he is leaving office and voters have already rendered their verdict on his administration by electing¬†Donald Trump¬†to a second term. voice_to_text: I can't remember the last time I received good service in a public establishment like I genuinely can but yeah I can't bring myself to not tip I know a lot of people don't tip they receive bad service they just they just withhold the tip and I'm not shaming anybody that does that I just I have to tip and I think we're just in a time now where people are so depressed and everybody hates their lives so much that nobody's putting in any effort in their jobs anymore there's no point in putting in an effort in a job where you're making so little money that you can't pay any bills that you have so I'm I'm still tipping I'm still tipping 20% and if I happen to receive fabulous service those people gonna get 30% I guess but nobody's nice anymore nobody's friendly nobody brings you what you ask for because everything just fucking sucks and I don't even I really don't even blame anybody for that because I have worked in the service industry and if I had to work in the service industry right now I don't know what kind of mental state that I would be in because I can't imagine relying on tips in an economy where people don't have money to tip or most people don't even have money to go out in the first place
